The assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand, the heir to the Austro-Hungarian Empire, by Gavrilo Princip, a member of the Serbian nationalist group called the Black Hand, was the catalyst that ignited World War I. Despite diplomatic efforts to resolve the conflict, the event led to a series of alliances and tensions among European powers, culminating in the declaration of war between Austria-Hungary and Serbia, subsequently involving numerous other countries. A lesser-known factor is that Princip might not have had the opportunity to assassinate Ferdinand had the Archduke's driver not taken a wrong turn and stopped to reverse, putting Ferdinand directly in Princip's path.

